17
00:00:54,680 --> 00:00:56,540
So let's do this.

18
00:00:56,540 --> 00:00:57,890
So what did we do before?

19
00:00:57,890 --> 00:01:00,620
When we worked on
a sum rule, we saw

20
00:01:00,620 --> 00:01:06,940
that if we count the union of
a whole collection of sets that

21
00:01:06,940 --> 00:01:10,170
are all disjoints, then we can
just some all the cardinalities

22
00:01:10,170 --> 00:01:12,290
of each of the members.

23
00:01:12,290 --> 00:01:17,110
So in the case where we have
intersections-- so sets are not

24
00:01:17,110 --> 00:01:20,440
disjoint-- well, if you just
count all the cardinalities--

25
00:01:20,440 --> 00:01:22,500
all of the sizes of
the sets together--

26
00:01:22,500 --> 00:01:25,190
you'll start to do
some double counting.

27
00:01:25,190 --> 00:01:27,600
So with the
inclusion-exclusion principle,

28
00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:33,130
we can actually exactly
compute the cardinality

29
00:01:33,130 --> 00:01:34,300
of the union of sets.

30
00:01:34,300 --> 00:01:37,910


31
00:01:37,910 --> 00:01:40,020
And you will see that
this principle can

32
00:01:40,020 --> 00:01:45,010
be used in plenty of examples,
including some of them that

33
00:01:45,010 --> 00:01:46,050
are on the problem set.

34
00:01:46,050 --> 00:01:49,740


35
00:01:49,740 --> 00:01:51,740
So how does it work?

36
00:01:51,740 --> 00:01:54,950
So let's set take an example
where we just have two sets

37
00:01:54,950 --> 00:01:57,050
and they have an intersection.

38
00:01:57,050 --> 00:02:01,550
So say this is one set which
we call M, and say here

39
00:02:01,550 --> 00:02:07,450
is another set which
we call E. Well, they

40
00:02:07,450 --> 00:02:10,530
have an intersection-- there's
some overlap over here.

41
00:02:10,530 --> 00:02:12,650
So if you would
like to write out

42
00:02:12,650 --> 00:02:15,720
the different areas
over here, what

43
00:02:15,720 --> 00:02:19,870
they were equal to, well, this
is everything that is in M,

44
00:02:19,870 --> 00:02:29,610
but we exclude what is in E.
So you write it M backslash E.

45
00:02:29,610 --> 00:02:32,940
This part over here
is the intersection

46
00:02:32,940 --> 00:02:35,910
of-- this maybe is a little
bit too small-- so this is

47
00:02:35,910 --> 00:02:37,335
the intersection of both sets.

48
00:02:37,335 --> 00:02:42,320


49
00:02:42,320 --> 00:02:44,710
And over here we have
everything that's

50
00:02:44,710 --> 00:02:49,330
in E but excluding what is in
M. So if you just write out

51
00:02:49,330 --> 00:02:50,960
the cardinalities of
the different sets

52
00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:52,543
that we're interested
in-- so we would

53
00:02:52,543 --> 00:02:56,680
like to compute the cardinality
of the union of M and E.

54
00:02:56,680 --> 00:03:01,490
So let's have a look
how the cardinality of M

55
00:03:01,490 --> 00:03:02,590
itself can be computed.

56
00:03:02,590 --> 00:03:08,890
Well, if you use the sum rule
which says that we can simply

57
00:03:08,890 --> 00:03:14,120
add the two disjoint
sets that make up set M--

58
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:16,560
we can count each of
those cardinality--

59
00:03:16,560 --> 00:03:21,510
so we have M consisting of this
part, which is M excluding E,

60
00:03:21,510 --> 00:03:25,550
plus the part that is right
here which is the intersection.

61
00:03:25,550 --> 00:03:29,900
So we use the sum
rule and conclude

62
00:03:29,900 --> 00:03:36,670
that we have the sum
of everything that's

63
00:03:36,670 --> 00:03:39,980
in M excluding E
plus the cardinality

64
00:03:39,980 --> 00:03:42,020
of the intersection.

65
00:03:42,020 --> 00:03:45,560
Now, for set E we can do
something completely similar.

66
00:03:45,560 --> 00:03:47,920
So we will have
everything that's

67
00:03:47,920 --> 00:03:52,190
in E excluding what
is in M. And then

68
00:03:52,190 --> 00:03:55,540
we still have the intersection.

69
00:03:55,540 --> 00:04:01,810
Now we are interested in the
union of the sent M and E.

70
00:04:01,810 --> 00:04:05,440
And now we need to add
this one this one and this

71
00:04:05,440 --> 00:04:06,220
once together.

72
00:04:06,220 --> 00:04:07,280
So what do we see?

73
00:04:07,280 --> 00:04:09,970
We see that this is
actually equal to everything

74
00:04:09,970 --> 00:04:13,630
that is in M but not
in E, everything that

75
00:04:13,630 --> 00:04:17,294
is in their intersection,
plus everything

76
00:04:17,294 --> 00:04:20,810
that's in E but not in M.

77
00:04:20,810 --> 00:04:25,110
So we have these equations
that we can directly derived

78
00:04:25,110 --> 00:04:27,150
from the sum rule.

79
00:04:27,150 --> 00:04:31,900
And, well, now we can
see here that if we

80
00:04:31,900 --> 00:04:36,330
are going to simply add-- that's
what the sum rule would say--

81
00:04:36,330 --> 00:04:40,340
simply add the
cardinality of M and of E,

82
00:04:40,340 --> 00:04:42,520
well, if we add
those two together,

83
00:04:42,520 --> 00:04:45,240
we will count the
intersection double.

84
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:48,680
So we'll need to cancel that
because it's only counted once

85
00:04:48,680 --> 00:04:50,780
in the union.

86
00:04:50,780 --> 00:04:56,400
So if we combine those three
over here-- those three

87
00:04:56,400 --> 00:05:06,850
equations-- then we can conclude
that this counts the set

88
00:05:06,850 --> 00:05:10,320
M intersecting with E twice.

89
00:05:10,320 --> 00:05:14,770
So we have that
the union is really

90
00:05:14,770 --> 00:05:18,980
equal to the cardinality
of M plus that

91
00:05:18,980 --> 00:05:23,280
of E minus their intersection.

92
00:05:23,280 --> 00:05:25,650
Now we can generalize this.

93
00:05:25,650 --> 00:05:27,460
And we will give
one more example

94
00:05:27,460 --> 00:05:34,240
where we have three sets and it
will give the general equation.

95
00:05:34,240 --> 00:05:37,780
So suppose you have
three sets now.

96
00:05:37,780 --> 00:05:42,840
Like one, another one,
and another one over here.

97
00:05:42,840 --> 00:05:48,790
So we have M, E, and,
say, the set S. Well,

98
00:05:48,790 --> 00:05:52,880
let's have a look how many
times these different areas--

99
00:05:52,880 --> 00:05:56,380
they're all disjoint--
how many times they

100
00:05:56,380 --> 00:06:04,100
are counted when me add the
three cardinalities together.

101
00:06:04,100 --> 00:06:08,760
So we have M plus
the cardinality of E

102
00:06:08,760 --> 00:06:11,600
plus the cardinality
of S. Well, if you

103
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:14,430
do that then we count
this area exactly

104
00:06:14,430 --> 00:06:19,020
once because it's in M, this
area we count once because it's

105
00:06:19,020 --> 00:06:23,360
in M and another time because
it's in E-- so it's twice--

106
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:25,820
this particular area
is only counted once

107
00:06:25,820 --> 00:06:28,080
in this sum over here.

108
00:06:28,080 --> 00:06:31,160
And similarly, we have two
times over here, two times here,

109
00:06:31,160 --> 00:06:32,980
and one times over here.

110
00:06:32,980 --> 00:06:36,840
And this intersection
of all of the three,

111
00:06:36,840 --> 00:06:39,580
well, it's counted when
we count elements in M

112
00:06:39,580 --> 00:06:41,445
but also when we
count elements in E

113
00:06:41,445 --> 00:06:43,870
and also when we
count elements in S.

114
00:06:43,870 --> 00:06:47,700
So this is counted three times.

115
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:50,260
So let's have a look.

116
00:06:50,260 --> 00:06:53,460
It seems like we want to
do exactly the same as what

117
00:06:53,460 --> 00:06:55,390
we did before.

118
00:06:55,390 --> 00:07:01,532
We like to subtract an
intersection of M and S.

119
00:07:01,532 --> 00:07:02,240
That's this part.

120
00:07:02,240 --> 00:07:05,440
It cancels the double
counting in this area, right?

121
00:07:05,440 --> 00:07:08,490
We can subtract this
intersection such that this

122
00:07:08,490 --> 00:07:10,520
part is cancelled.

123
00:07:10,520 --> 00:07:12,340
The double counting
here is canceled.

124
00:07:12,340 --> 00:07:14,290
And similarly, we
want to subtract

125
00:07:14,290 --> 00:07:17,750
the intersection between
E and S which would

126
00:07:17,750 --> 00:07:19,300
eliminate this double counting.

127
00:07:19,300 --> 00:07:22,090
But now we can see that
we start to subtract

128
00:07:22,090 --> 00:07:29,030
too much because this central
area here will be-- well,

129
00:07:29,030 --> 00:07:31,000
it's part of each of
those intersections

130
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:35,130
so it's actually eliminated.

131
00:07:35,130 --> 00:07:38,310
All of it is subtracted.

132
00:07:38,310 --> 00:07:41,490
So let's create
the same diagram.

133
00:07:41,490 --> 00:07:47,370
But now when we count the sum
of all those intersections--

134
00:07:47,370 --> 00:07:52,840
so we have the
intersection of M intersect

135
00:07:52,840 --> 00:07:58,450
with E, the intersection
of M with S,

136
00:07:58,450 --> 00:08:01,480
and we also want to figure
out how many times elements

137
00:08:01,480 --> 00:08:09,570
are counted in the set
E intersects with S.

138
00:08:09,570 --> 00:08:10,490
So let's have a look.

139
00:08:10,490 --> 00:08:13,830
Well, this area here
is counted zero times.

140
00:08:13,830 --> 00:08:17,330
It's not part of any
of these intersections

141
00:08:17,330 --> 00:08:21,950
because it-- this part is
only in M and not in S or E.

142
00:08:21,950 --> 00:08:25,020
So this is counted zero times.

143
00:08:25,020 --> 00:08:27,530
And here we have the same.

144
00:08:27,530 --> 00:08:29,530
Well, this part over
here is exactly once

145
00:08:29,530 --> 00:08:31,980
in this intersection
between those two sets.

146
00:08:31,980 --> 00:08:35,710
It's not in this one so
this is counted once.

147
00:08:35,710 --> 00:08:39,030
So we have by symmetry
that for all the others.

148
00:08:39,030 --> 00:08:42,809
This area, however, is in both
this intersection as well as

149
00:08:42,809 --> 00:08:44,200
this one and also this one.

150
00:08:44,200 --> 00:08:47,270
So it's counted three times.

151
00:08:47,270 --> 00:08:51,540
So now we can easily start to
combine all these together.

152
00:08:51,540 --> 00:08:58,490
And you can see, if we take
this sum and we subtract this,

153
00:08:58,490 --> 00:09:00,020
then the middle
area is cancelled.

154
00:09:00,020 --> 00:09:03,180
So we have to still add the
intersection of the three sets.

155
00:09:03,180 --> 00:09:07,030
The intersection of
M, E and S together.

156
00:09:07,030 --> 00:09:11,060
So in a formula that
would look like this.

157
00:09:11,060 --> 00:09:15,040
So we are interested
in the union.

158
00:09:15,040 --> 00:09:17,930


159
00:09:17,930 --> 00:09:20,540
And this can now be
written as, well,

160
00:09:20,540 --> 00:09:26,000
the sum of the cardinalities
of the individual sets.

161
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:32,830
And we subtract
the intersections

162
00:09:32,830 --> 00:09:34,160
that we have up there.

163
00:09:34,160 --> 00:09:38,743
So M intersect E
minus M intersect

164
00:09:38,743 --> 00:09:44,780
with S and minus E
intersect with S.

165
00:09:44,780 --> 00:09:48,256
Now we have eliminated-- if
you look at this Venn diagram

166
00:09:48,256 --> 00:09:49,755
over here-- this
diagram over here--

167
00:09:49,755 --> 00:09:52,950
we've eliminated everything
that's in the middle area.

168
00:09:52,950 --> 00:09:56,130
So we still need to add
intersection-- everything that

169
00:09:56,130 --> 00:10:02,220
is counted in the intersection
of M, E, as well as S.

170
00:10:02,220 --> 00:10:03,940
So we have this equation.

171
00:10:03,940 --> 00:10:07,390
And now you can see why we call
this the inclusion-exclusion

172
00:10:07,390 --> 00:10:08,700
principle.

173
00:10:08,700 --> 00:10:15,510
Here we include all the
elements in M, E and S.

174
00:10:15,510 --> 00:10:18,800
Now we have to exclude
what we counted too much.

175
00:10:18,800 --> 00:10:22,310
So we have exclusion over here.

176
00:10:22,310 --> 00:10:24,830
And now we, again, have
to include some stuff

177
00:10:24,830 --> 00:10:29,080
because we excluded too much.

178
00:10:29,080 --> 00:10:31,430
And then we keep
on going like this.

179
00:10:31,430 --> 00:10:39,420
So, in general, we get
the following theorem

180
00:10:39,420 --> 00:10:43,640
that says that, if you
look at the cardinalities--

181
00:10:43,640 --> 00:10:48,770
of the cardinality of the union
of a whole bunch of sets--

182
00:10:48,770 --> 00:10:54,490
say we have n sets-- then this
is actually equal to-- well,

183
00:10:54,490 --> 00:10:59,900
we first include the sums of all
the individual cardinalities.

184
00:10:59,900 --> 00:11:08,960
Which is from I equals 1 to n
cardinality of Ai minus-- now

185
00:11:08,960 --> 00:11:11,270
we have to, again,
we have to eliminate

186
00:11:11,270 --> 00:11:16,820
all the double counting-- so
we look at every pair of sets

187
00:11:16,820 --> 00:11:19,580
indexed by i1 and i2.

188
00:11:19,580 --> 00:11:22,690
And we look at
their intersection

189
00:11:22,690 --> 00:11:26,320
and we take that out
using this minus sign.

190
00:11:26,320 --> 00:11:27,430
We exclude this.

191
00:11:27,430 --> 00:11:30,240


192
00:11:30,240 --> 00:11:31,350
And we continue like this.

193
00:11:31,350 --> 00:11:35,250
So we add now-- because
we have excluded too much,

194
00:11:35,250 --> 00:11:39,850
we have to include
some more-- we

195
00:11:39,850 --> 00:11:45,860
look at all triples of sets
indexed by i1, i2-- oops--

196
00:11:45,860 --> 00:11:46,650
and i3.

197
00:11:46,650 --> 00:11:49,820


198
00:11:49,820 --> 00:11:54,110
And now we look at the
intersection of those sets.

199
00:11:54,110 --> 00:11:58,400


200
00:11:58,400 --> 00:12:02,030
And we continue like
this all the way

201
00:12:02,030 --> 00:12:09,170
until we look at the very last
intersection that you can have,

202
00:12:09,170 --> 00:12:12,830
which is intersection
of all the sets.

203
00:12:12,830 --> 00:12:17,790
And it depends on whether
n is even or add whether we

204
00:12:17,790 --> 00:12:20,040
have to include or exclude it.

205
00:12:20,040 --> 00:12:24,520
So we have a minus 1
to the power n plus 1.

206
00:12:24,520 --> 00:12:29,950
And then we have the
intersection of all of these.

207
00:12:29,950 --> 00:12:34,900
Now, we can write this out
in a more elegant formula

208
00:12:34,900 --> 00:12:40,690
where we just put all this
what I wrote here in a sum.

209
00:12:40,690 --> 00:12:42,010
And then it looks like this.

210
00:12:42,010 --> 00:12:47,310
It's the sum over k
equals 1 to n minus 1

211
00:12:47,310 --> 00:12:49,460
to the power k plus 1.

212
00:12:49,460 --> 00:12:51,540
So depends whether
k is even or odd

213
00:12:51,540 --> 00:12:55,570
whether we do an inclusion
or an exclusion in this sum.

214
00:12:55,570 --> 00:13:03,870
And we look at all the subsets
that our subsets of the index

215
00:13:03,870 --> 00:13:11,220
set 1 up to n such that the
cardinality of the set S

216
00:13:11,220 --> 00:13:13,440
is equal to k.

217
00:13:13,440 --> 00:13:18,430
And now we need to look at
the cardinality of all--

218
00:13:18,430 --> 00:13:23,880
of the intersection of all the
sets that are indexed by S.

219
00:13:23,880 --> 00:13:31,265
So that's-- so I run-- I put i--
so do the intersection of all i

220
00:13:31,265 --> 00:13:34,630
in S of the sets Ai.

221
00:13:34,630 --> 00:13:39,430
So this general formula is the
inclusion-exclusion principle.

222
00:13:39,430 --> 00:13:40,930
And this is the way
how we can think

223
00:13:40,930 --> 00:13:42,980
about it how to derive it.

224
00:13:42,980 --> 00:13:45,140
Of course, this is not a proof.

225
00:13:45,140 --> 00:13:48,250
But you could do this
yourself by using induction.

226
00:13:48,250 --> 00:13:50,700
And you can use induction on n.

227
00:13:50,700 --> 00:13:55,250
So that's a pretty
straightforward exercise.

228
00:13:55,250 --> 00:13:55,750
OK.

229
00:13:55,750 --> 00:13:57,385
So let's give an example.

230
00:13:57,385 --> 00:14:00,180


