00:31:15,990 --> 00:31:18,180
And it's the
binomial coefficients

502
00:31:18,180 --> 00:31:26,250
where we choose four
out of the 16 symbols.

503
00:31:26,250 --> 00:31:30,180
And this is equal to 16
factorial divided by 4

504
00:31:30,180 --> 00:31:32,110
factorial times 12 factorial.

505
00:31:32,110 --> 00:31:35,570


506
00:31:35,570 --> 00:31:43,730
Now we often also denote
the following rule--

507
00:31:43,730 --> 00:31:47,310
we sort of identify
as a special case.

508
00:31:47,310 --> 00:31:53,740
We say that the number of
k elements-- of k element

509
00:31:53,740 --> 00:32:06,420
subsets-- of an n element set
is actually equal to n choose k.

510
00:32:06,420 --> 00:32:09,840


511
00:32:09,840 --> 00:32:12,120
So this is an important
rule to remember

512
00:32:12,120 --> 00:32:13,615
which will occur many times.

513
00:32:13,615 --> 00:32:22,370


514
00:32:22,370 --> 00:32:23,780
OK.

515
00:32:23,780 --> 00:32:26,590
A theorem that we can have
derived from all this stuff

516
00:32:26,590 --> 00:32:29,510
is what we call the
binomial theorem.

517
00:32:29,510 --> 00:32:31,020
So we'll quickly go over that.

518
00:32:31,020 --> 00:32:37,090


519
00:32:37,090 --> 00:32:41,580
The binomial theorem says
that, for all integers n--

520
00:32:41,580 --> 00:32:46,840
positive integers n-- we have
a plus b to the power n equals

521
00:32:46,840 --> 00:32:52,320
to the sum where we
take k from 0 to n

522
00:32:52,320 --> 00:32:57,250
and then we have the
binomial where we

523
00:32:57,250 --> 00:32:58,900
have this expression over here.

524
00:32:58,900 --> 00:33:06,840
We choose k out of n
and we choose, say, k

525
00:33:06,840 --> 00:33:08,982
times b in this expression.

526
00:33:08,982 --> 00:33:10,690
I will explain in a
moment by an example.

527
00:33:10,690 --> 00:33:13,630
And n minus k ace.

528
00:33:13,630 --> 00:33:15,170
And this is the theorem.

529
00:33:15,170 --> 00:33:17,300
And I will just
give an example just

530
00:33:17,300 --> 00:33:22,300
to show how we can
think about this.

531
00:33:22,300 --> 00:33:23,510
So let me do that over here.

532
00:33:23,510 --> 00:33:26,050


533
00:33:26,050 --> 00:33:31,595
So if you take n
equals to 2, then we

534
00:33:31,595 --> 00:33:34,830
can see that we get all the
combinations, essentially,

535
00:33:34,830 --> 00:33:36,380
of a and b of length 2.

536
00:33:36,380 --> 00:33:42,420
So you have a times a, a times
b, b times a, and b times b.

537
00:33:42,420 --> 00:33:44,300
So what do we see?

538
00:33:44,300 --> 00:33:51,470
We see a squared plus ab
plus ba plus b squared.

539
00:33:51,470 --> 00:33:56,980
Now we see that these have 1
times an a and 1 times a b.

540
00:33:56,980 --> 00:34:01,660
This one has 2 times an a
and this one has 2 times a b.

541
00:34:01,660 --> 00:34:04,420


542
00:34:04,420 --> 00:34:08,449
And this combines together
as a squared plus 2 times

543
00:34:08,449 --> 00:34:11,340
ab plus b squared.

544
00:34:11,340 --> 00:34:16,179
Now, if you have n equals 3--
so we have a plus b to the power

545
00:34:16,179 --> 00:34:22,100
3-- you will get all
the different products,

546
00:34:22,100 --> 00:34:26,889
all the different terms,
that add up to this,

547
00:34:26,889 --> 00:34:29,940
are all the kinds of
combinations of a's and b's.

548
00:34:29,940 --> 00:34:36,880
So for example, we have three
a's-- so 3 times a-- but it can

549
00:34:36,880 --> 00:34:47,739
also have a squared times b
plus aba plus b a squared.

550
00:34:47,739 --> 00:34:53,840
And those have exactly two
times an a and one times a b.

551
00:34:53,840 --> 00:34:57,650
I can now look at
all the others--

552
00:34:57,650 --> 00:35:00,600
so I may have two times
the b and one times the a.

553
00:35:00,600 --> 00:35:02,570
So what our those?

554
00:35:02,570 --> 00:35:11,570
We have a times b squared
plus bab plus b squared a.

555
00:35:11,570 --> 00:35:16,550
So I count these
as the same, right?

556
00:35:16,550 --> 00:35:19,340
They each have the
same number of b's.

557
00:35:19,340 --> 00:35:22,510
Two times the b and
one times the a.

558
00:35:22,510 --> 00:35:27,110
And then, finally, I
have b to the power 3

559
00:35:27,110 --> 00:35:29,120
which counts three times the b.

560
00:35:29,120 --> 00:35:31,120
So these are all the
possible terms that I have.

561
00:35:31,120 --> 00:35:32,510
There are eight in total.

562
00:35:32,510 --> 00:35:35,436
One, two, three, four,
five, up to eight.

563
00:35:35,436 --> 00:35:36,310
And that fits, right?

564
00:35:36,310 --> 00:35:39,877
Because I can have a
choice of an a and a b.

565
00:35:39,877 --> 00:35:40,960
And I do that three times.

566
00:35:40,960 --> 00:35:43,440
So 2 times 2 times
2 is equal to 8.

567
00:35:43,440 --> 00:35:45,090
So I have eight terms.

568
00:35:45,090 --> 00:35:50,170
And I can group them together
by taking a to the power 3

569
00:35:50,170 --> 00:35:57,080
plus 3 times a squared
b plus 3 times-- and now

570
00:35:57,080 --> 00:36:04,830
I have b squared a-- and
finally, b to the power 3.

571
00:36:04,830 --> 00:36:06,980
So what do we see here?

572
00:36:06,980 --> 00:36:09,860
How many terms are their
that have exactly two times

573
00:36:09,860 --> 00:36:11,630
an a and one times a b?

574
00:36:11,630 --> 00:36:17,370
Well, it's like we have a
set of three elements, right?

575
00:36:17,370 --> 00:36:20,470
Or three positions.

576
00:36:20,470 --> 00:36:22,250
And I like two of
them to be an a.

577
00:36:22,250 --> 00:36:24,580
So I choose two out of
those three to be an a.

578
00:36:24,580 --> 00:36:30,870
So I use this subset rule
to count how many times I

579
00:36:30,870 --> 00:36:35,270
see the same term back.

580
00:36:35,270 --> 00:36:42,650
So let's write this
out so that is-- so

581
00:36:42,650 --> 00:36:50,960
the number of terms
that have k times an a,

582
00:36:50,960 --> 00:36:56,120
and we have, say, n
minus k times a b.

583
00:36:56,120 --> 00:36:58,680
So how many terms do I have?

584
00:36:58,680 --> 00:37:09,700
Well, that is the length
of-- so the number of-- oops.

585
00:37:09,700 --> 00:37:10,280
Change that.

586
00:37:10,280 --> 00:37:16,320
So it's the number
of length n sequences

587
00:37:16,320 --> 00:37:18,350
that have the
following property.

588
00:37:18,350 --> 00:37:27,220
That these have k a's
and n minus k b's.

589
00:37:27,220 --> 00:37:29,390
And that's easy to count.

590
00:37:29,390 --> 00:37:32,120
Which is equal to what
we have done here before.

591
00:37:32,120 --> 00:37:36,700
We have the binomial n choose k.

592
00:37:36,700 --> 00:37:39,130
And that, if you plug
that in over here,

593
00:37:39,130 --> 00:37:42,400
then we get this particular sum.

594
00:37:42,400 --> 00:37:44,980
So it is-- this is
the binomial theorem.

595
00:37:44,980 --> 00:37:46,910
Very famous.

596
00:37:46,910 --> 00:37:49,960
And now we're going
to use all this stuff

597
00:37:49,960 --> 00:37:51,660
to count some poker hands.

598
00:37:51,660 --> 00:37:55,440
So we have come to this
part of the lecture.

599
00:37:55,440 --> 00:37:57,740
So we're going to do
a bunch of examples

600
00:37:57,740 --> 00:37:59,830
that are similar
to some of those

601
00:37:59,830 --> 00:38:01,460
that you will see
in the problem set.

602
00:38:01,460 --> 00:38:03,145
And then at the end
we go and continue

603
00:38:03,145 --> 00:38:07,190
with some-- with a
different proof technique.

604
00:38:07,190 --> 00:38:16,260
So let's first define
a deck of cards

605
00:38:16,260 --> 00:38:18,870
because that's what we
are going to use now.

606
00:38:18,870 --> 00:38:26,430
So for this type of
problems, we will

607
00:38:26,430 --> 00:38:34,810
use a deck which is
actually a set of 52 cards.

608
00:38:34,810 --> 00:38:44,490
And a card itself
actually has a suit.

609
00:38:44,490 --> 00:38:47,140
And the suit can
be something that

610
00:38:47,140 --> 00:38:51,170
looks like this, which
is called spades.

611
00:38:51,170 --> 00:38:52,970
S of spades.

612
00:38:52,970 --> 00:38:58,500
We have another symbol
which is this, hearts.

613
00:38:58,500 --> 00:39:06,670
And we will have clubs
and we have diamonds.

614
00:39:06,670 --> 00:39:10,970
And besides a suit, a
card also has a value.

615
00:39:10,970 --> 00:39:21,030
And the values are arranged from
2, 3, 4, all the way up to 10.

616
00:39:21,030 --> 00:39:24,440
Then we have a special
symbol-- special value--

617
00:39:24,440 --> 00:39:26,600
which is called the Jack.

618
00:39:26,600 --> 00:39:31,030
We've got a Queen and a
King and finally the Ace.

619
00:39:31,030 --> 00:39:35,930
And in total, we have
13 possible values.

620
00:39:35,930 --> 00:39:38,930
So you can see that
we have four times,

621
00:39:38,930 --> 00:39:41,900
because of four different
suits, 4 times 13

622
00:39:41,900 --> 00:39:46,330
is 52 different cards
and that makes up a deck.

623
00:39:46,330 --> 00:39:49,450
So we're going to look at hands.

624
00:39:49,450 --> 00:39:55,605
And a hand is actually
a collection-- a set

625
00:39:55,605 --> 00:39:57,720
of five cards.

626
00:39:57,720 --> 00:40:04,560
So it's a subset of
the deck of five cards.

627
00:40:04,560 --> 00:40:09,310
And we do not worry
about the order

628
00:40:09,310 --> 00:40:11,290
of the cards in your hand.

629
00:40:11,290 --> 00:40:13,210
They can be permuted,
if you want.

630
00:40:13,210 --> 00:40:15,480
So the order's not important.

631
00:40:15,480 --> 00:40:19,750
So it's a subset of five cards.

632
00:40:19,750 --> 00:40:21,460
So how many hands do I have?

633
00:40:21,460 --> 00:40:24,130


634
00:40:24,130 --> 00:40:26,550
Well, how many ways
are there to choose

635
00:40:26,550 --> 00:40:31,740
a subset of five cards
out of a deck of 52 cards?

636
00:40:31,740 --> 00:40:33,900
Well, we can use
a subset through

637
00:40:33,900 --> 00:40:37,670
and we get the
binomial 52 choose 5.

638
00:40:37,670 --> 00:40:41,150


639
00:40:41,150 --> 00:40:44,900
Which is, by the way, a lot so
let me write it out as well.

640
00:40:44,900 --> 00:40:47,710
It's about 2 and 1/2 million.

641
00:40:47,710 --> 00:40:53,430


642
00:40:53,430 --> 00:40:57,280
So we are interested
in, when we play poker--

643
00:40:57,280 --> 00:41:01,450
if you do that-- in
really good hands.

644
00:41:01,450 --> 00:41:03,920
So we like four of
a kind, which means

645
00:41:03,920 --> 00:41:09,420
that we have four cards that
actually have the same value.

646
00:41:09,420 --> 00:41:14,160
Or we have cards
that-- hands that have

647
00:41:14,160 --> 00:41:15,270
what we call a full house.

648
00:41:15,270 --> 00:41:17,120
We will count those in a moment.

649
00:41:17,120 --> 00:41:20,240
Or other kinds of combinations.

650
00:41:20,240 --> 00:41:26,170
And the rarer the combination
is in your hand, the higher

651
00:41:26,170 --> 00:41:29,820
or the better your hand
is, and the more likely

652
00:41:29,820 --> 00:41:33,080
it is that you win
the poker game.

653
00:41:33,080 --> 00:41:35,550
If you do not get left out.

654
00:41:35,550 --> 00:41:36,050
All right.

655
00:41:36,050 --> 00:41:41,000


656
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:48,030
So let's give an example
of a four of a kind.

657
00:41:48,030 --> 00:41:49,840
So we're going to
compute those and we

658
00:41:49,840 --> 00:41:52,350
will see that we need to do--
to use all the-- a combination

659
00:41:52,350 --> 00:41:53,183
for all these rules.

660
00:41:53,183 --> 00:42:02,260


661
00:42:02,260 --> 00:42:04,600
OK.

662
00:42:04,600 --> 00:42:11,180
So four of a kind
is the special hand

663
00:42:11,180 --> 00:42:19,245
where we have four
of one kind of value.

664
00:42:19,245 --> 00:42:23,210


665
00:42:23,210 --> 00:42:26,200
Notice, by the way, that the
fifth card, because of this,

666
00:42:26,200 --> 00:42:28,440
must have a different
value, right?

667
00:42:28,440 --> 00:42:31,780
Because there are
only four cards

668
00:42:31,780 --> 00:42:34,090
that have, say, the value eight.

669
00:42:34,090 --> 00:42:37,030
Because there are only
four different suits.

670
00:42:37,030 --> 00:42:38,540
So the fifth card
will ultimately

671
00:42:38,540 --> 00:42:41,650
have a different value.

672
00:42:41,650 --> 00:42:49,310
So as an example, we will have
the 8 of spades and then the 9

673
00:42:49,310 --> 00:42:52,930
of diamonds and all the
other 8's-- the 8 of diamonds

674
00:42:52,930 --> 00:42:55,930
and the 8 of hearts and,
say, the 8 of clubs.

675
00:42:55,930 --> 00:42:58,440


676
00:42:58,440 --> 00:43:01,820
And how do we count
these types of hands?

677
00:43:01,820 --> 00:43:04,620
We're going to look
for a representation

678
00:43:04,620 --> 00:43:08,070
of how can you represent
such hands, such objects?

679
00:43:08,070 --> 00:43:11,120
So we have to count a
special type of object,

680
00:43:11,120 --> 00:43:13,310
a special kind of poker hand.

681
00:43:13,310 --> 00:43:15,800
And in order to do
that, we're going

682
00:43:15,800 --> 00:43:20,190
to look for a way to
represent these objects

683
00:43:20,190 --> 00:43:24,450
and in such a way that we
can count them very easily.

684
00:43:24,450 --> 00:43:26,530
And that's really
the trick in order

685
00:43:26,530 --> 00:43:29,500
to solve these kinds
of counting problems.

686
00:43:29,500 --> 00:43:32,680
So the representation
that we have here is--

687
00:43:32,680 --> 00:43:36,420
well, we can choose--
first of all,

688
00:43:36,420 --> 00:43:46,430
we can choose the value of the
four kinds-- of the four cards.

689
00:43:46,430 --> 00:43:49,970
So how many choices do I have?

690
00:43:49,970 --> 00:43:53,820
Well, I got any choice.

691
00:43:53,820 --> 00:43:57,990
There are 13 different
values so I have 13 choices.

692
00:43:57,990 --> 00:44:01,260
So that's easy.

693
00:44:01,260 --> 00:44:06,510
Secondly, I can choose the
value of the extra card.

694
00:44:06,510 --> 00:44:10,920


695
00:44:10,920 --> 00:44:13,310
So how many choices
do I have here?

696
00:44:13,310 --> 00:44:18,450
Well, the four of a kind already
eliminates one kind of value

697
00:44:18,450 --> 00:44:19,100
completely.

698
00:44:19,100 --> 00:44:19,600
Right?

699
00:44:19,600 --> 00:44:25,020
So I have any of the
other values is possible.

700
00:44:25,020 --> 00:44:27,370
Is equally likely, even.

701
00:44:27,370 --> 00:44:30,670
So I have 12 choices.

702
00:44:30,670 --> 00:44:35,870
And, lastly, I can represent--
I need to still represent

703
00:44:35,870 --> 00:44:37,280
the suit of the extra card.

704
00:44:37,280 --> 00:44:43,279
So I also want to know the
suit of the extra card.

705
00:44:43,279 --> 00:44:44,570
And how many choices do I have?

706
00:44:44,570 --> 00:44:47,080
Well, I can choose
any of those four.

707
00:44:47,080 --> 00:44:49,970
So that's four.

708
00:44:49,970 --> 00:44:52,110
So, essentially, what
we constructed here

709
00:44:52,110 --> 00:44:57,830
is a mapping by using
this representation.

710
00:44:57,830 --> 00:45:03,510
And the mapping tells
us-- is as follows.

711
00:45:03,510 --> 00:45:06,040


712
00:45:06,040 --> 00:45:07,292
Let's keep this up.

713
00:45:07,292 --> 00:45:15,330


714
00:45:15,330 --> 00:45:21,390
So the mapping goes from poker
hands-- from card-- from hands

715
00:45:21,390 --> 00:45:27,940
to-- from hands with four of
a kind to this representation.

716
00:45:27,940 --> 00:45:29,480
So let's write it out.

717
00:45:29,480 --> 00:45:33,960
So we have four of a kind.

718
00:45:33,960 --> 00:45:36,080
And then we have a
function-- a mapping

719
00:45:36,080 --> 00:45:39,240
f-- that goes to
this representation.

720
00:45:39,240 --> 00:45:43,020
We will have the first
entry-- the value 1

721
00:45:43,020 --> 00:45:45,795
and the value 2
and then a value 3.

722
00:45:45,795 --> 00:45:48,930


723
00:45:48,930 --> 00:45:54,780
So for example, if you
take this hands of cards,

724
00:45:54,780 --> 00:46:01,820
well, the first one, we see that
the four of a kind has value 8.

725
00:46:01,820 --> 00:46:06,860
The value of the second card is
