I see that n minus 1 choose k
minus 1 plus n minus 1 choose

1261
01:19:18,070 --> 01:19:23,270
k should be equal to--
well, before I counted it

1262
01:19:23,270 --> 01:19:29,330
as this-- so it should
be equal to n choose k.

1263
01:19:29,330 --> 01:19:32,495
And this is called
Pascal's Identity.

1264
01:19:32,495 --> 01:19:35,820


1265
01:19:35,820 --> 01:19:39,110
And the general idea is is
that we do the following.

1266
01:19:39,110 --> 01:19:46,710
So we are actually counting
a set in two different ways.

1267
01:19:46,710 --> 01:19:49,990
That's what we did so far.

1268
01:19:49,990 --> 01:19:52,980
And when you solve
these types of problems,

1269
01:19:52,980 --> 01:19:58,740
the difficulty is that you
will need to define the set S.

1270
01:19:58,740 --> 01:20:00,240
So usually you
get a problem, you

1271
01:20:00,240 --> 01:20:03,830
need to prove some
equation like this.

1272
01:20:03,830 --> 01:20:07,790
So you define a set S.
That's the hard part of it.

1273
01:20:07,790 --> 01:20:12,590
Then we are going to show
that the cardinality of S

1274
01:20:12,590 --> 01:20:17,550
is some number n,
say, in one way.

1275
01:20:17,550 --> 01:20:19,770
So we have one
method to do this.

1276
01:20:19,770 --> 01:20:20,680
By counting.

1277
01:20:20,680 --> 01:20:23,870


1278
01:20:23,870 --> 01:20:33,210
And we will show that S is also
equal to some other number--

1279
01:20:33,210 --> 01:20:35,260
like, in this case,
we had one number

1280
01:20:35,260 --> 01:20:38,600
and this was my second
one-- also by counting.

1281
01:20:38,600 --> 01:20:43,270
And then we can
conclude that n--

1282
01:20:43,270 --> 01:20:47,532
so we conclude that n equals m.

1283
